er code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def uniqueOccurrences(self, arr: List[int]) -> bool:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom collections import Counter\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def uniqueOccurrences(self, arr: List[int]) -> bool:\n        # Count the occurrences of each value in the array\n        occurrences = Counter(arr).values()\n        # Check if the number of occurrences is unique\n        return len(occurrences) == len(set(occurrences))\n```\n\nThis solution uses the `Counter` class from the `collections` module to count the occurrences of each value in the array. It then checks if the length of the occurrences list is equal to the length of the set of occurrences. If they are equal, it means all occurrences are unique, and the function returns `true`; otherwise, it returns `false`.", "estimated_date": 1569715200000}